\fs24 \cf0 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\b\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 The historical accuracy
\f1\b0 \'a0of Aristotle's claim is debated. The Socrates we encounter in Plato's middle-period dialogues (
\f2\i Phaedo
\f1\i0 ,\'a0
\f2\i Republic
\f1\i0 )\'a0
\f2\i does
\f1\i0 \'a0separate the Forms. Aristotle may be reading his own categories onto the history of philosophy, or distinguishing the early "Socratic" phase of Plato's thought from the later "Platonic" one.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\fs24 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\b\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 The evidence is all second-hand.
\f1\b0 \'a0We have no autograph Socratic writings. What we know of Socrates' method comes from Plato, Xenophon, and Aristotle himself \'97 so this attribution rests on Aristotle's testimony, not on independent Socratic texts.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\fs24 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\b\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 Aristotle says the Pythagoreans defined before Socrates
\f1\b0 , but dismisses their efforts as "soft and without method" (\uc0\u956 \u945 \u955 \u945 \u954 \u8182 \u962  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u7936 \u956 \u949 \u952 \u972 \u948 \u969 \u962 ). The first to define\'a0
\f2\i systematically
\f1\i0 \'a0is what Socrates is credited with.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\fs24 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\b\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 Diogenes Laertius
\f1\b0 \'a0confirms the biographical tradition that Socrates "introduced ethics" (\uc0\u964 \u8052 \u957  \u7968 \u952 \u953 \u954 \u8052 \u957  \u949 \u7984 \u963 \u945 \u947 \u945 \u947 \u972 \u957 \u964 \u959 \u962 ) \'97 consistent with Aristotle's statement that he "occupied himself with the ethical virtues" \'97 but does not discuss the technical method of induction and definition in Aristotle's terms. (Eulogikon: rjo-ab, ref. Vit.2.16)\
\ls2\ilvl0
\fs24 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\b\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 What would settle the open questions?
\f1\b0 \'a0Independent evidence of Socrates' method from a non-Platonic, non-Aristotelian source would be needed \'97 and none survives.---\
